      "seed": 883636382,
      "version": 1042,
      "versionNonce": 2064202882,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1773729203499,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "   2. use redis, atomically increase the counter using INCR. \n   \n        Depending on the scale, it matters. 100M DAU = 1k req/seconds.\n10k req in worst case per second. : best can be handled by redis. \n\nThe only issue is predicatability in the system. Security concern.\n\n\n3. better appraoch use of snowflake ids. Keep that in system. Keep 64 bits, some are for timestamp and then use unique atomically increasing integer. \n\n4. make redirects fast:\n\n   1. keep an index on shorturl in postgres or dynamo DB\n   2. use redis, it is only helpful when repeated traffic is coming. Disk IO will not be there, everything will be catered through\nmain memory. \n   3. use of CDN: this is also a cache. It is very near to user, so latency can be further reduced. \n     ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "   2. use redis, atomically increase the counter using INCR. \n   \n        Depending on the scale, it matters. 100M DAU = 1k req/seconds.\n10k req in worst case per second. : best can be handled by redis. \n\nThe only issue is predicatability in the system. Security concern.\n\n\n3. better appraoch use of snowflake ids. Keep that in system. Keep 64 bits, some are for timestamp and then use unique atomically increasing integer. \n\n4. make redirects fast:\n\n   1. keep an index on shorturl in postgres or dynamo DB\n   2. use redis, it is only helpful when repeated traffic is coming. Disk IO will not be there, everything will be catered through\nmain memory. \n   3. use of CDN: this is also a cache. It is very near to user, so latency can be further reduced. \n     ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
