    {
      "id": "ovW7Z9LJ500aApFU35rwz",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2079.7475783163463,
      "y": -13410.69809062057,
      "width": 947.1985473632812,
      "height": 650,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b04",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1039108290,
      "version": 1256,
      "versionNonce": 211328770,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1773729624808,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Data flow:\n\nclient -> api service \n   few options:\n1. rate limiting on client side: only if client is our own service, usually not possible\n2. api side: should be some centralized server, has more context about the incoming request. \n3. api gateway layer: this is the best for basic rate limiting. On the basis of clientid, api key and all. \n\n\nfunction call is best. Using rpc. \n\nrateLimit(String endpoint, String clientId, Requestheaders headers)\n   - it includes timestamp and all.\n\nTwo scenarios: \n  1. if allowed then pass, add headers requests_pending in a second\n  2. 429: retry after. Throttling in place. \n\nHigh level design:\n\n\n1. There are multiple algos for rate limiting:\n     1. token bucket: tokens incoming rate per second, max bucket size.\n     2. sliding window\n     3. fixed window\n     4. leaky bucket: bucket size fixed, leaking buckets allow only specific amount of requests in some time.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Data flow:\n\nclient -> api service \n   few options:\n1. rate limiting on client side: only if client is our own service, usually not possible\n2. api side: should be some centralized server, has more context about the incoming request. \n3. api gateway layer: this is the best for basic rate limiting. On the basis of clientid, api key and all. \n\n\nfunction call is best. Using rpc. \n\nrateLimit(String endpoint, String clientId, Requestheaders headers)\n   - it includes timestamp and all.\n\nTwo scenarios: \n  1. if allowed then pass, add headers requests_pending in a second\n  2. 429: retry after. Throttling in place. \n\nHigh level design:\n\n\n1. There are multiple algos for rate limiting:\n     1. token bucket: tokens incoming rate per second, max bucket size.\n     2. sliding window\n     3. fixed window\n     4. leaky bucket: bucket size fixed, leaking buckets allow only specific amount of requests in some time.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "aLfbA0ViPeO_HGsC9_h_2",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2083.901760799197,
      "y": -12687.870338604458,
      "width": 1166.87841796875,
      "height": 375,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b05",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 919742018,
      "version": 898,
      "versionNonce": 2094441310,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1773729854984,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "The best, token bucket.\nStore some config, clientId_endpoint { lastTimeStampOfFill, pendingRequests}\n                                 endpoint_bucket {maxSize, tokenCountPerSecond}\n\none option is to store in memory of api gateway.\nMultiple gateway can create issue. As we want centralized control.\n\nUse fast Data layer: redis. \n   store as key value pairs. \n\nFor concurrency: use lua scripts or exec kind of commands to have transactional semantics. Then only return. It is going to be real \nfast as redis is involved. <10ms. \nKeep redis close to api gateway one option, as clientIds are usually located in one geographical reason. \n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "The best, token bucket.\nStore some config, clientId_endpoint { lastTimeStampOfFill, pendingRequests}\n                                 endpoint_bucket {maxSize, tokenCountPerSecond}\n\none option is to store in memory of api gateway.\nMultiple gateway can create issue. As we want centralized control.\n\nUse fast Data layer: redis. \n   store as key value pairs. \n\nFor concurrency: use lua scripts or exec kind of commands to have transactional semantics. Then only return. It is going to be real \nfast as redis is involved. <10ms. \nKeep redis close to api gateway one option, as clientIds are usually located in one geographical reason. \n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
